<p>46% of all Google searches have local intent. That is billions of searches per day from people looking for businesses near them. The companies that show up in the <a href="/glossary/local-pack/">local pack</a> and Google Maps capture 75% of those clicks. Everyone else splits the rest.</p>
<p>Most local businesses know SEO matters but do not know where to start. They optimize one thing, skip ten others, and wonder why nothing changes. A local SEO checklist fixes that. It gives you every step in order, with nothing missed.</p>
<p>This local SEO checklist covers 40 actionable steps across 8 categories. Every item is something you can complete yourself or hand to your team. We built this from our experience publishing 3,500+ blog posts across 70+ industries with a 92% average SEO score.</p>
<p>Here is what this checklist covers:</p>
<ul>
<li>Google Business Profile optimization (the single biggest ranking factor)</li>
<li>On-page SEO for local keywords</li>
<li>Citation building and NAP consistency</li>
<li>Review generation and management</li>
<li>Local content strategy</li>
<li>Technical SEO fundamentals</li>
<li>Link building for local businesses</li>
<li>Tracking and measurement</li>
</ul>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Local pack ranking factors breakdown for 2026 showing GBP, reviews, and on-page signals" src="/images/blog/local-seo-ranking-factors-2026.webp" /></p>
<h2>Google Business Profile Checklist</h2>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile</a> accounts for 32% of local pack ranking factors. This is the single most impactful category. Start here.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Google Business Profile optimization checklist for local SEO" src="/images/blog/local-seo-gbp-checklist.webp" /></p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Claim and verify your profile.</strong> Go to business.google.com. Verify by postcard, phone, email, or video. Unverified profiles do not appear in the local pack.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Set your primary business category.</strong> Choose the most specific option. "Italian Restaurant" outperforms "Restaurant." The primary category is the <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/learn/google-local-algorithm-and-ranking-factors/">top ranking factor</a> for the local pack.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add secondary categories.</strong> Add every relevant category. A plumber who also does drain cleaning and water heater installation should list all three.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Write a complete business description.</strong> Use all 750 characters. Mention your city, services, and experience. Do not stuff keywords.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add every service individually.</strong> List each service with a brief description and price range. Google uses this data for search matching.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Set accurate business hours.</strong> Include special hours for holidays. Outdated hours frustrate customers and signal neglect to Google.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Upload 15+ photos.</strong> Team shots, office or storefront, completed work, products, and before-and-after images. Businesses with photos get 42% more direction requests.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Enable messaging.</strong> Let customers contact you through Google directly. Response time affects your visibility.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Post 2-3 times per week.</strong> Share tips, offers, project highlights, and announcements. See our <a href="/blog/gbp-posting-frequency/">GBP posting frequency guide</a> for a detailed schedule.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Reply within 24 hours. Thank positive reviewers. Address negative reviews professionally. Use our <a href="/tools/review-response-generator/">review response generator</a>.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Your SEO team. $99/month.</strong> 30 optimized articles, published automatically. GBP posts included with Local SEO.
<a href="/pricing/">Start for $1 →</a></p>
</blockquote>
<h2>On-Page SEO Checklist</h2>
<p><a href="/glossary/on-page-seo/">On-page signals</a> account for 15% of local pack ranking factors and are the dominant factor for local organic results. Your website must tell Google what you do and where you do it.</p>
<h3>Service Pages</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Create a dedicated page for each service.</strong> "Roof Repair" gets its own page. "AC Installation" gets its own page. One page per service.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Include [city] + [service] in every title tag.</strong> Format: "[Service] in [City] | [Business Name]." Keep under 60 characters.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Write <a href="/blog/write-meta-descriptions/">meta descriptions</a> for every page.</strong> 145 to 155 characters. Include your primary keyword and a benefit statement.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Use H1, H2, H3 headers in correct hierarchy.</strong> One H1 per page. Multiple H2s for sections. H3s under H2s. Never skip levels.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Write 300+ words of unique content per service page.</strong> Describe your process, what is included, and why customers choose you. No thin content.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add before-and-after photos</strong> with descriptive alt text that includes your keyword and city.</li>
</ul>
<h3>City and Location Pages</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Create a page for each city you serve.</strong> Target "service + city" combinations on each page.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Write unique content for each city page.</strong> Mention neighborhoods, zip codes, and local details. Do not copy-paste with only the city name changed.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Embed a Google Map</strong> showing your service area or office location.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add <a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">LocalBusiness schema markup</a></strong> on every location page with your name, address, phone, hours, and service area.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Sitewide On-Page</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Place your NAP in the footer of every page.</strong> Name, address, and phone number visible sitewide.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal links</a> between service pages, city pages, and blog posts.</strong> 3 to 5 internal links per page minimum.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Optimize images.</strong> Compress to under 200KB. Use WebP format. Add descriptive alt text with local keywords.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Citation and Directory Checklist</h2>
<p><a href="/glossary/citation/">Citations</a> are online mentions of your business name, address, and phone number. They account for 7% of local pack ranking factors, but inconsistencies can actively harm your rankings.</p>
<h3>Core Directories</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to Google Business Profile</strong> (already covered above).</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to Bing Places.</strong> Second largest search engine. Free to list.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to Apple Maps.</strong> Growing mobile search share. Submit through Apple Business Connect.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to Yelp.</strong> Claim and complete your free profile.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to Facebook Business.</strong> Create a business page with accurate NAP.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to BBB (Better Business Bureau).</strong> Trust signal and <a href="/glossary/e-e-a-t/">E-E-A-T</a> boost.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Industry-Specific Directories</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to 10+ industry-specific directories.</strong> Restaurants: TripAdvisor, OpenTable. Home services: Angi, Thumbtack. Healthcare: Healthgrades, Zocdoc. Find your industry's top directories.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Submit to local directories.</strong> Chamber of commerce, local business associations, city directories, and neighborhood sites.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a href="/glossary/nap/">NAP</a> Consistency</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Audit NAP consistency across all listings.</strong> Your business name, address, and phone number must be identical everywhere. "123 Main St" and "123 Main Street" are different to Google.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Fix inconsistencies immediately.</strong> Use <a href="/best/local-citation-tools/">local citation tools</a> to scan and identify mismatches. Correct every one.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Use one phone number everywhere.</strong> Do not mix office, cell, and tracking numbers across directories.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Review Management Checklist</h2>
<p>Reviews now account for 20% of local pack ranking factors, up from 16% in 2023. This is the fastest-growing ranking signal. <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">68% of consumers will not use a business rated below 4 stars</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Set up a review generation system.</strong> Do not wait for reviews to happen. Send a text or email request within 24 hours of service completion.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Create a direct review link.</strong> Google provides a short URL for your review page. Share it via text message for the highest conversion rate.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Add a review QR code to printed materials.</strong> Use our <a href="/tools/review-qr-code-generator/">review QR code generator</a> and place it on invoices, business cards, and receipts.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Target 2-4 new reviews per month.</strong> Review velocity (how often you get new reviews) matters as much as total count.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Respond to every review within 24 hours.</strong> Positive and negative. Responses show potential customers you are engaged and professional.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Never buy fake reviews.</strong> Google detects and removes them. Getting caught can result in profile suspension.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Monitor review platforms beyond Google.</strong> Check Yelp, Facebook, and industry-specific sites monthly.</li>
</ul>
<p>For 21 specific strategies, see our <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">complete guide to getting more Google reviews</a>.</p>
<h3>How Reviews Affect Rankings in 2026</h3>
<p>Google weighs review signals more heavily than ever. The 2026 BrightLocal study shows reviews grew from 16% to 20% of local pack ranking factors. Three specific review metrics influence rankings:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Quantity.</strong> More reviews signal popularity. Target 50+ reviews for local pack eligibility.</li>
<li><strong>Quality.</strong> Average rating matters. The sweet spot is 4.5 stars. A perfect 5.0 looks suspicious.</li>
<li><strong>Recency.</strong> New reviews every month signal an active, trusted business. Stale review profiles (last review 6+ months ago) lose positioning.</li>
</ul>
<p>Review content also feeds AI Overviews. Google's AI pulls from review text to generate local business summaries. Detailed reviews that mention specific services and locations give Google more data to work with.</p>
